{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_kale_ver01/data/2017236974/00279558078/1945083001/0780.xml":{"full_text":"Fish Patrol on Iheya Shima\nMarino Privates First Class Raymond E.i Cranford (left) of\n'Greensboro, N. C., and Joseph H. Prunier of Linwood, Mass.,\nw\u00bbtch with interest as an Iheya Shima native cleans a fish haul.\nShe two Leathernecks accompanied a native fishing party from\nthe island in the Okinawa group when the Iheyans went out to\nIncrease a dwindling food supply. (U. S. Marine Corps Photo)\nFacts Worth Knowing About\nUnemployment Compensation\nIN NORTH CAROLINA\nMore Than\u2014\n800.000 North Carolinians have\nprotection against wage-loss.\nMore Than\u2014\n$105,000,000 is available for bene\nfit payments when needed.\nMore Than\u2014\n10.000 employers pay the taxes\nthat support this fund.\nMore Than\u2014\n3.800.000 claims have been paid.\nMore Than\u2014\n300.000 individuals have received\nunemployment comp e n s a t i o n\nchecks.\nMore Than\u2014\n100 percent of covered workers\ncurrently employed could be paid\nan average benefit amount for\nthe duration of 16 weeks.\nAND\nNATIONALLY\nMore Than\u2014\nSix billions have been accumu\nlated in state unemployment\ncompensation reserves.\nMore Than\u2014\n18,000,000 workers could be sup\nported by these state funds with\naverage benefits for maximum\ndurations.\nNEVERTHELESS\n\u2022m Mr _\n4UUI C\nWorkers in North Carolina are\nwithout unemployment insurance\n^protection than those who have\nit including workers for small\nfirms, for non-profit institutions,\nin government (state, city and\ncounty) and domestic service,\nand farm workers.\nMore\u2014\nIn Benefits could be paid from\nthe North Carolina fund without\nendangering its solvency in the\npostwar period, when the unem\nployed may face more than 16\nweeks without employment.\nImplement And\nTractor Tires\nBeen Released\nTractor and Implement tires\nhave been released from rationing,\nC. K. Kelly, Chairman, Halifax\nCounty AAA Committee, announc\ned here today. \u201cFarmers using\ntruck and passenger tires will con\ntinue to obtain them through local\nOPA boards,\u201d he said. Distribu\ntion control of Crawler tractors\nwas discontinued August 20. \u201cNo\napplications for Crawler tractors\nhave been approved since July\n28,\u201d Kelly said, \"and all applica\ntions that were not approved will\nbe mailed directly to applicants\nby the War Production Board.\u201d\n\u201cAll applications in State and\nCounty AAA Offices will be re\nturned to applicants immediately,\u201d\nhe added.\nRoanoke Rapids\nMan Promoted\nWith the 722nd Railway Operat\ning Battalion, Bremen, Germany\u2014\nLarther L. Medlin, 1021 Franklin\nStreet, Roanoke Rapids, N. C., has\nbeen promoted to the grade of\ncorporal in the 722nd Railway op\nerating Battalion. He is a brake\nman with the 722nd, which super\nvises and operates railroads in the\nBremen Enclave, port of supply\nAnnouncing removal of office;\nTo 915 Roanoke Ave.\nNext to Tickle\u2019s Barber Shop\nNew Phone R-6986\nClosed Mondays until 5 P. M.\nDr. E. D. Harbour\nOptometrist\nRoanoke Rapids, N. GL\n\nfor American occupation forces in\nGermany. Cpl. Medlin arrived in\nFrance with the battalion in Aug\nust, 1944, and aided in sending\nsupplies to the front through four\nmajor campaigns in France, Bel\ngium and Germany. Before en\ntering the Army in October, 1943,\nCpl. Medlin was employed by the\nAtlantic Coast Line Railroad as a\nbrakeman. His wife, Mrs. Jessie E.\nMedlin, resides at the Franklin\nStreet address in Roanoke Rapids.\nA hick town is a place where\ngroups of ladies discuss sin, but\nseem to assume there is only one\nkind.\nAmerica has no suicide pilots,\nunless you count the poor guys\nwho test the new jet planes.\nPeople never cheer a preacher,\nfor he never says \u201cthis handsome\nand intelligent audience.\u201d\nThe atomic bombs can\u2019t be made\nmuch larger. We have no bombu\nfast enough to get out of the way.\n1 111 I\nJtEDDY KILOWATT Gotroks Got Reddy VIRGINIA ELECTRIC POWER CO.\nPOOR MRS. GOTROKS HAD MORE DOlfcU THAN AUJE BAkCERIES.\nLEFT HEB^^^oS^W'PlANIS-WEHlieOWJFFKJ^\nWOU DONT LHWE TO\nUA MRS. GOTROKC TO 1\nAFFORD 13 SERVANTS-'\nREDDY KILOWATT Vour\nElectric Servant, CAN DO\nIN ONE KILOWATT HOUR AC\nMUCH AC TOE COMBINED EFFORTS\nof 13 PEOPLE IN AN HOUR.\nAN AVERAGE O/y\nKltOWATT ,1\nHOUR. U\nCOSTS ONiy...\n-\u2014i~-\u2014\u2014 \u2014i-'\u2014\u2022*\u2014 r\nCALL TO FARMS!\nVICTORY in Eurcne\nhas not decreased the\ndemand for food. Vcl- q\nunteers are needed to\nhelp harvest every\npound of our war crops\n\u2014nothing must be\nwasted. Last year, mil\nlions of people with no\nexperience in farm work volunteered to help farmers harvest vital\nwar crops. This year, farm goals call for a towering rate of produc- t\ntion\u2014and it can be reached only with the willing help of millions\nmore like you. You'll be paid for your time, of course. The work will\nnot be too strenuous for you. If you can spend the summer, or a\nmonth, or even your vacation period on a farm\u2014apply to your\ncounty agent or local farm employment office. If you can work on\na farm in spare time, or week ends, watch for announcements of\nlocal emergencies in your community.\nListen to the ''Summer Electric Hour,'' with Robert\nArmbi*uster's Orchestra, every Sunday afternoon. 4:30\nP. M., CBS Network.\nvmw/a &&7X/C amp 'cmmwv","height":"21576","width":"14336"}}
